<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-827-354  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 827 354.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Sept 3 1990 n285 p55(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>March to a different drummer. (John Perry Barlow comes to thedefense of computer hacker Craig Neidorf)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Caldwell, Bruce.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>John Perry Barlow came to the defense of Craig Neidorf after thefederal government filed charges against Neidorf for publishinginformation it claimed was stole from BellSouth Corp's 911emergency telephone services in his electronic magazine Phrack.andO;Barlow saw the case as an assault on civil liberties and was ableto enlist the aid of Lotus Development Corp founder Mitch Kapor,who in turn enlisted the aid of an attorney he knew.andP;  The attorneyinvestigated the case and others arising from Operation Sun Devil,which the attorney called an assault on the Constitution; thecharges against Neidorf were dropped on Jul 27, 1990, after it wasshown that anyone with a computer could access BellSouth data.andO;Barlow and Neidorf met through an electronic forum sponsored byHarper's magazine titled Is Computer Hacking a Crime? Barlow'sreport on the encounter was distributed on the WELL forum, anelectronic bulletin board, which is where it caught Kapor's eye.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer Bulletin BoardsComputer HackersLegal IssuesCourt CasesFreedom of Information.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   John Barlow. (portrait)Person:    Neidorf, Craig (cases); Barlow, John Perry (attitudes); Kapor,Mitchell (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>